A core is an independent processing unit inside a CPU that can run instructions in parallel.
Think of it like this:
🧠 CPU = the brain
💪 Core = a worker inside the brain
A CPU can have:
1 core (old / tiny machines)
4, 8, 16, 64+ cores (modern servers)
Each core can do one unit of work at a time.

What does “1 core” mean in Prometheus?
When you see CPU usage expressed in cores, it means:
How many full CPU cores are being used continuously
Examples:
0.1 → using 10% of one core
0.5 → using half of a core
1.0 → using one full core
2.0 → using two full cores
4.0 → using four full cores
0.7 on 1 core → OK
0.9 on 1 core → risky
1.8 on 2 cores → overloaded
2.5 on 4 cores → healthy
⚠️ Real-time systems should never live at 90–100% CPU.
WebSockets / live dashboards
Streaming analytics
Online gaming backends
Trading dashboards (not execution engines)
IoT data ingestion
Chat systems
👉 Typical CPU need:
1–4 cores
Missing deadlines makes results useless, but doesn’t crash the world.
Examples:
Video/audio processing pipelines
Live ML inference
Telecom signaling
Industrial monitoring
👉 Typical CPU need:
2–8 cores
Deadlines must never be missed.
Examples:
Robotics control loops
Medical devices
Avionics
Automotive ECUs
👉 Typical CPU need:
Often dedicated cores
RTOS or real-time Linux
Core count depends on tasks, but isolation matters more than count
